Collaborate on Designs & Prototypes

01
On this page
  1. Tools for collaborating on accessible code prototypes
    1. Design Systems vs. Pattern Libraries vs. Style Guides
  2. Building Blocks of Digital Design Systems

Collaborating on designs and prototypes with an engineering focus is an excellent approach to moving accessibility efforts forward in an organization. A visual design, a wireframe, or even a light code implementation provides the necessary tooling for a productive conversation about accessibility.

The goal is to prevent access barriers from being passed on to development when they could have been tweaked or rethought earlier. This can cut down on the number of feedback loops involved with creating an accessible solution, thus saving time and money in the long run (and who doesn’t love that?).

Tools for collaborating on accessible code prototypes

Designs or wireframes can be a great start to facilitating a conversation about technical feasibility for accessibility.

One step further is having working code prototypes. Working code prototypes can be powerful because you can validate if a pattern or approach works from the keyboard, a screen reader, or other Assistive Technology.

There are a number of great tools for collaborating on code prototypes, starting with plain old HTML, CSS, and JavaScript shared with your internal team. Using real code is important for accessibility prototype discussions, as opposed to clickable designs that don’t represent accessible user interactions (like InVision or similar).

Parcel is a useful tool for bundling libraries and custom code together should you need to rig up something more sophisticated but still simpler than integrating with your entire tech stack. Codepen and similar hosted platforms can provide spaces for quick implementation and discussion, including private demos for limiting access to relevant stakeholders. And then there is Storybook.

Storybook is a tool for UI development. It allows individuals and teams to create organized UI systems, making the building process and documentation more efficient and easier to use. Entire UIs can be developed without needing to start up an entire dev stack, force specific data into your database, or navigate around your application.

Design Systems vs. Pattern Libraries vs. Style Guides

Code prototypes for designs typically focus on select components or portions of user flows–it’s what makes them fast to develop and gather feedback. These smaller units, when finessed and approved to move forward, could become great initial patterns for implementation as part of a library.

When collaborating across teams on such libraries and collections, you'll likely hear the following terms:

  • A design system is a complete set of standards, docs, and principles along with UI patterns and components to achieve those standards
  • A pattern library represents components in a design system
  • A style guide is a document with rules or standards for graphic style, color, typography, iconography, imagery, and brand principles with direction on how to use it

The main takeaway is that looking at individual components and documentation are both opportunities for accessibility to be improved, hopefully not forgotten.

Building Blocks of Digital Design Systems

Design systems present a unique opportunity to build accessibility and inclusion into your component libraries from the get-go, both from a UI/UX design perspective and from a development perspective.

These are some opportunities to get accessibility right from the beginning in a design system:

  • Color and design aesthetics
  • Type readability
  • Semantic structure within components
  • Text alternatives
  • Interactivity
  • Configurability and flexibility
  • Documentation
